"Fahse L., Heurich M.","Simulation and analysis of outbreaks of bark beetle infestations and their management at the stand level",2011,"Ecological Modelling","222","11",,"1833","1846",,,10.1016/j.ecolmodel.2011.03.014,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79955088130&partnerID=40&md5=7197cbe8b5cb73bf0385d82754f17316","Forest Ecology, ETH Zurich, 8092 Zurich, Switzerland; Bavarian Forest National Park, 94481 Grafenau, Germany","Fahse, L., Forest Ecology, ETH Zurich, 8092 Zurich, Switzerland; Heurich, M., Bavarian Forest National Park, 94481 Grafenau, Germany","Outbreaks of bark beetles in forests can result in substantial economic losses. Understanding the factors that influence the development and spread of bark beetle outbreaks is crucial for forest management and for predicting outbreak risks, especially with the expected global warming. Although much research has been done on the ecology and phenology of bark beetles, the complex interplay between beetles, host trees, beetle antagonists and forest management makes predicting beetle population development especially difficult. Using the recent infestations of the European Spruce Bark Beetle (Ips typographus L. Col. Scol.) in the Bavarian Forest National Park (Germany) as a case study, we developed a spatially explicit agent-based simulation model (SAMBIA) that takes into account individual trees and beetles. This model primarily provides a tool for analysing and understanding the spatial and temporal aspects of bark beetles outbreaks at the stand scale. Furthermore, the model should allow an estimation of the effectiveness of concurrent impacts of both antagonists and management to confine outbreak dynamics in practice. We also used the model to predict outbreak probabilities in various settings. The simulation results indicated a distinct threshold behaviour of the system in response to pressure by antagonists or management of the bark beetle population. Despite the different scenarios considered, we were able to extract from the simulations a simple rule of thumb for the successful control of an outbreak: if roughly 80% of individual beetles are killed by antagonists or foresters, outbreaks will rarely take place. Our model allows the core dynamics of this complex system to be reduced to this inherent common denominator. © 2011 Elsevier B.V.","Antagonists; Bark beetle; Ips typographus; Management; Outbreaks; Spatial simulation model; Threshold behaviour","Antagonists; Bark beetle; Ips typographus; Outbreaks; Spatial simulation; Threshold behaviour; Computer simulation; Forecasting; Forestry; Global warming; Losses; Parks; Research and development management; beetle; coniferous tree; economic analysis; estimation method; forest management; global warming; host plant; infectious disease; management practice; numerical model; pest species; phenology; plant-herbivore interaction; population structure; pressure effect; spatiotemporal analysis; threshold; Forecasts; Forestry; Germany; Insects; Losses; Management; Simulation; Bavaria; Bavarian Forest National Park; Germany; Coleoptera; Ips typographus; Picea; Scolytinae",,,,,,"Anderbrant, O., Dispersal of reemerged spruce bark beetles, Ips typographus (Coleoptera, Scolytidae): a mark-recapture experiment (1985) Zeitschrift für Angewandte Entomologie, 99, pp. 21-25; Anderbrant, O., Schlyter, F., Birgersson, G., Intraspecific competition affecting parents and offspring in the bark beetle Ips typographus (1985) Oikos, 45, pp. 89-98; Aukema, B.H., Carroll, A.L., Zhu, J., Raffa, K.F., Sickley, T.A., Taylor, S.W., Landscape level analysis of mountain pine beetle in British Columbia, Canada: spatiotemporal development and spatial synchrony within the present outbreak (2006) Ecography, 29, pp. 427-441; Baier, P., Pennerstorfer, J., Schopf, A., PHENIPS-a comprehensive phenology model of Ips typographus (L.) (Col., Scolytinae) as a tool for hazard rating of bark beetle infestation (2007) Forest Ecology and Management, 249, pp